Chima Azubuike, Gombe The Deputy Governor of Gombe State, Dr Manassah Jatau, has said the state would examine its current tax laws as a measure to boost its internally generated revenue. Jatau stated this on Thursday, in an interview with our correspondent in Gombe. He said it was part of measures to improve the earnings of the state. The deputy governor said, “As a government, we have a the sole responsibility of making sure investors have conducive environment to operate as well as a task to check loopholes. “We have been trying to get investors to the state. Private investors are the only people that can create employment. “The role of government is just to create a conducive atmosphere for investors to operate. “There is a limit to which we can employ civil servants. Already we are trying to look at tax laws to improve our Internally Generated Revenue, “We will try to block loopholes. As a government, we will take a look at mineral resources. “There are many people that are mining illegally. You are aware that what we get from the Federal Government is not that much.” Copyright PUNCH.
